  "summary": {
    "verdict": "BLOCK",
    "one_liner": "Financial payout function has three production-critical bugs: floating-point currency math, no negative payout guard, and no NaN/null input validation — any of which can cause incorrect bank transfers."
  },

  "critical_findings": [
    {
      "title": "Floating-point arithmetic on currency values causes silent money loss/gain",
      "risk": "JavaScript IEEE-754 floating-point math accumulates rounding errors across iterations. For a courier with 80+ deliveries/week, errors compound per-iteration and the final payout sent to the bank will be cents off — in aggregate across thousands of couriers, this is material financial discrepancy.",
      "severity": "Critical",
      "location": "calculateWeeklyPayout, lines 5-8 (accumulation loop) and line 11 (commission multiplication)",
      "reproduction": "Simple example: 0.1 + 0.2 === 0.30000000000000004. Chain 80 additions/subtractions of real-world cent values (e.g., basePay=12.10, bonusPay=3.30, deductions=1.10) and the final sum drifts. Multiply by 0.15 for commission and the error compounds again.",
      "fix": "Represent all monetary values as integers in cents (or use a Decimal library like dinero.js / big.js). Convert: totalEarnings += Math.round(delivery.basePay * 100), do all math in cents, divide by 100 only at the final return. Alternatively, round the final payout: Math.round(payout * 100) / 100 as a minimum safeguard.",
      "time_to_fix": "30 minutes",
      "acceptance_criteria_affected": "Payout amount must be accurate to the cent for bank transfer initiation"
    },
    {
      "title": "No guard against negative payout — could initiate a negative bank transfer",
      "risk": "If a courier's deductions exceed basePay + bonusPay (e.g., damage chargebacks, equipment fees), totalEarnings goes negative. Commission on a negative number becomes a negative deduction (reducing the magnitude), and the function returns a negative payout. Depending on the downstream bank transfer API, this could either fail silently, throw an unhandled error, or worse — initiate a debit/clawback from the courier's account.",
      "severity": "Critical",
      "location": "calculateWeeklyPayout, return statement — no Math.max(0, payout) or equivalent guard",
      "reproduction": "Create a courier with one delivery: basePay=5.00, bonusPay=0, deductions=20.00. totalEarnings = -15.00, commission = -2.25, payout = -12.75. This negative value is passed directly to the bank transfer.",
      "fix": "Add: const safePayout = Math.max(0, payout); return safePayout; — and log/flag the negative balance for manual review or carry-forward to next pay period. Negative balances are a business logic decision that must not silently flow into a payment API.",
      "time_to_fix": "15 minutes",
      "acceptance_criteria_affected": "Payout value used for bank transfer must be non-negative"
    },
    {
      "title": "No input validation — NaN/undefined fields produce a NaN payout sent to bank",
      "risk": "If any delivery record has a null, undefined, or non-numeric basePay/bonusPay/deductions (e.g., a DB migration added a new field with null default, or a partial record), arithmetic with undefined produces NaN. NaN propagates through every subsequent operation silently — the function returns NaN, which is then used to initiate a bank transfer of NaN dollars.",
      "severity": "Critical",
      "location": "calculateWeeklyPayout, lines 5-8 — no validation on delivery fields before arithmetic",
      "reproduction": "Insert a delivery record where bonusPay is null (common after schema migration). undefined + 5 = NaN. The entire payout becomes NaN. typeof NaN === 'number' so naive type checks pass.",
      "fix": "Validate each field: const base = Number(delivery.basePay) || 0; const bonus = Number(delivery.bonusPay) || 0; const deduct = Number(delivery.deductions) || 0; — and add a post-loop guard: if (Number.isNaN(totalEarnings)) throw new Error('Invalid earnings calculation for courier ' + courierId); to fail loudly rather than send garbage to the bank.",
      "time_to_fix": "15 minutes",
      "acceptance_criteria_affected": "Payout calculation must never produce NaN or non-finite values"
    }
  ],

  "important_issues": [
    {
      "title": "Zero-delivery week may trigger a $0 bank transfer",
      "description": "If getWeekly returns an empty array (new courier, inactive week), the function returns 0. Depending on the bank transfer API, initiating a $0 transfer may incur fees, throw errors, or create confusing transaction records. Should short-circuit with an early return or skip transfer for zero payouts.",
      "location": "calculateWeeklyPayout, after deliveries fetch"
    },
    {
      "title": "Commission applied to gross including deductions — business logic may be wrong",
      "description": "The 15% commission is applied after deductions are subtracted. This means the platform earns less commission when couriers have deductions. Typical payout models apply commission to gross earnings (basePay + bonusPay) before deductions. If this is intentional, it should be documented; if not, the platform is systematically undercharging commission.",
      "location": "calculateWeeklyPayout, line 11"
    },
    {
      "title": "Hardcoded commission rate is a ticking time bomb",
      "description": "The 0.15 commission rate is hardcoded. When the business changes rates (per-market, per-tier, promotional), this requires a code deploy rather than a config change. Should be fetched from config or a courier-tier table.",
      "location": "calculateWeeklyPayout, line 11"
    }
  ],

  "suggestions": [
    "Wrap the entire function in a try/catch and log courierId on failure — a silent exception here means a courier doesn't get paid with no alert",
    "Add an idempotency key or calculation hash to prevent duplicate payouts if the function is retried",
    "Consider adding an audit log entry with the breakdown (gross, commission, deductions, net) for dispute resolution"
  ],

  "production_readiness": {
    "deployment_risks": "This function directly controls real money movement. All three critical findings can produce incorrect bank transfers under normal operating conditions — not edge cases.",
    "rollback_capability": "Code rollback is trivial but does not reverse incorrect bank transfers already initiated. Financial operations require pre-deployment validation, not post-deployment rollback.",
    "backward_compatibility": "Standalone function — no backward compatibility concerns with fixes.",
    "monitoring_coverage": "No logging, no metrics, no alerting. A NaN payout or negative transfer would be completely invisible until a courier complains.",
    "breaking_changes": {
      "api_breaking": false,
      "db_destructive": false,
      "shared_library": false,
      "auth_security": false,
      "data_pipeline": false,
      "config_changes": false,
      "details": []
    },
    "safe_to_deploy": false,
    "rollback_plan": "Do not deploy. Fix all three critical findings first. Incorrect payouts cannot be rolled back — money already transferred is gone."
  },

  "escalations": [],

  "confidence": {
    "level": 97,
    "high_confidence_areas": [
      "Floating-point arithmetic is a well-documented flaw for currency in JavaScript — this is not speculative",
      "Negative payout path is trivially reproducible with real-world deduction scenarios",
      "NaN propagation from null/undefined fields is a known JS behavior"
    ],
